    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1943-08-21T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1943-08-21T00:00:00-05:00" n="507"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d507">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">Hull Papers</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Draft of Joint Statement</hi>
                    <note n="1" xml:id="d507fn1">The source text is marked “Churchill draft” in
                        Hull’s handwriting. This draft and the three printed immediately below are
                        all undated but seem to have been prepared between Hull’s arrival at Quebec
                        on August 20, 1943, and the preparation of the draft on which Roosevelt
                        worked during the evening of August 22, <hi rend="italic">post</hi>, <ref
                            target="#pg_1106">p. 1106</ref>.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Quebec</hi>
                        </placeName>, [<date calendar="gregorian" when="1943-08-21">August 21 (?),
                            1943</date>.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>The United States and United Kingdom Governments have decided to recognize the
                    French Committee of National Liberation as the <pb facs="1216" n="1102"
                        xml:id="pg_1102"/> responsible authority representing all Frenchmen outside
                    France who are resolutely engaged in the expulsion from French soil of all
                    German forces and in the destruction of the Hitler régime.</p>
                <p>The two Governments have taken this action on the basis that the French Committee
                    of National Liberation themselves do not claim to represent the future
                    Government of France which can only be established after the French Nation in
                    conditions of freedom and tranquility has been able to express its wishes in a
                    constitutional form.</p>
                <p>During the continuance of the war military needs are paramount and all controls
                    necessary for operational purposes are in consequence reserved to the Supreme
                    Commander of the Allied Armies in any theatre of war.</p>
            </div>
